x4freetext: 7 MV Van de Graaff accelerator at the
Institute for Reference Materials and Measurements
Uranium sample of a thickness of 92 microg/cm2 was
produced through vacuum evaporation on gold-coated
235U (45 microg/cm2) are used for absolute energy
The neutron production is done using three nuclear
Measured neutron energies, reaction targets used,
fission cross section and counting statistics:
both analogue and digital data acquisition techniques.
Twin Frisch Grid Ionization Chamber (TFGIC) with two
anodes, two grids and a common cathode. As counting
gas P10 (90% Argon, 10% Methane) is used in continuous
Energies and angles of both fragments are measured
using the double E method, conservation of energy and
momentum is assumed to calculate FF masses.
Total kinetic energy TKE = 170.5 +/- 0.5 MeV and the
position of the mean heavy-mass peak at AH = 139.6 amu
at thermal induced fission of 235U are used for the
The final data analysis was mainly done for the digital
system, due to its superiority over the analogue data.
-The measured two-dimensional mass yield and TKE
distribution have been described in terms of fission
modes. The yield of the standard 1 (S1) mode shows
fluctuations in the threshold of the fission cross
section due to the influence of the resonance and
levels off at about 20% yield for higher incident
neutron energies. The S2 mode shows the respective
opposite behavior. The mean TKE of both modes
decreases with En. The decrease in mean TKE overrules
the increase in S1 yield, so the mean TKE is dropping
as a function of En above 2.5 MeV.
- Post-neutron-emission kinetic energy of HF as a
function of post-neutron-emission mass for En=5MeV is
mass yields for En=5MeV for HF and LF are presented
- TKE and mean pre-neutron-emission mass as function of
total NU for AV method ( see Subent 011) for EN=5MeV
are presented on fig.9a of J,PR/C,86,054601,2012.
